#compdef openapi-preprocessor
# =============================================================================
# openapi-preprocessor — Olivier Mengué's "Authoring tool for
#                        OpenAPI specifications" — a Go CLI
#                        for preprocessing OpenAPI 3.x YAML/
#                        JSON specs with custom keywords
#                        ($merge, $include, $ref-with-fragment,
#                        etc.) that resolve to a final clean
#                        OpenAPI document.  Enables modular
#                        OpenAPI authoring: split specs across
#                        files, share common schemas, generate
#                        per-environment variants.
#                        Distinguishing from cherrybomb (R669
#                        — security audit), openapi-generator
#                        (code generation), Swagger UI
#                        (visualization), and other OpenAPI
#                        tools by:
#                          - PREPROCESSOR DIRECTIVES via
#                            extended keywords in source YAML/
#                            JSON:
#                              * $merge      — deep-merge
#                                              referenced docs
#                              * $include    — inline file
#                                              contents
#                              * $ref        — JSON Pointer
#                                              with cross-file
#                                              fragment support
#                              * $cmd        — execute shell
#                                              commands (e.g.
#                                              git-rev-parse)
#                          - CROSS-FILE $ref RESOLUTION — JSON
#                            Pointer references across
#                            multiple source files merged
#                            into a single output document
#                          - DEEP-COPY semantics via
#                            mohae/deepcopy — referenced
#                            schema fragments deep-copied
#                            into the output, avoiding
#                            mutation of shared references
#                          - JSON Pointer SUPPORT via
#                            dolmen-go/jsonptr — RFC 6901
#                            JSON Pointer resolution for
#                            $ref / $include / $merge targets
#                          - YAML 1.2 INPUT + JSON OUTPUT —
#                            input documents typically YAML
#                            (preferred for human-authoring);
#                            output typically JSON (for tool
#                            interop); both supported via
#                            file extension detection
#                          - COMPACT JSON OUTPUT via -c /
#                            --compact-output — single-line
#                            JSON for CDN distribution
#                          - DEBUG TRACE via -debug=trace —
#                            shows document-navigation trace
#                            during preprocessing for
#                            troubleshooting unresolved $refs
#                          - VERSION INJECTION via ldflags —
#                            -X main.version=$(git describe)
#                            embeds version + git rev
#                          - GODOC-GENERATED MANPAGE —
#                            openapi-preprocessor.1 manpage
#                            generated via lufia/godoc2man
#                            from godoc comments
#                          - STDLIB `flag` PACKAGE — minimal
#                            CLI parsing (not cobra / urfave/
#                            cli; tiny binary footprint)
#                          - SINGLE-FILE main.go — entire CLI
#                            in main.go (~few hundred lines);
#                            preprocessor engine in pkg
#                        Used by: OpenAPI authors splitting
#                        large specs across files, microservice
#                        teams sharing common schemas across
#                        services, API gateway operators
#                        generating per-environment specs from
#                        a single source-of-truth document,
#                        and as a reference implementation of
#                        gopkg.in/yaml.v3 + dolmen-go/jsonptr +
#                        mohae/deepcopy + stdlib `flag`
#                        composition in Go.
#
# Author:  Olivier Mengué (dolmen@cpan.org, dolmen on GitHub) —
#          French Go + Perl developer.  Long-time CPAN
#          contributor.  License: MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/dolmen-go/openapi-preprocessor
#          https://github.com/dolmen-go/openapi-preprocessor/blob/master/main.go
#          https://github.com/dolmen-go/openapi-preprocessor/blob/master/go.mod
#          https://github.com/dolmen-go/openapi-preprocessor/blob/master/openapi-preprocessor.1
# CLI:     main.go — uses Go's stdlib `flag` package (not
#          cobra / urfave/cli; minimal footprint).  Headline
#          library: **gopkg.in/yaml.v3** (yaml.v3 is the new
#          variant being documented here, expanding Axis 20 —
#          YAML Parsing — to Go).
# Library: gopkg.in/yaml.v3 v3.0.1
#          ("go-yaml/yaml v3" — "YAML support for the Go
#           language" — originally by Gustavo Niemeyer
#           (Canonical Ltd / Ubuntu); now community-maintained.
#           Distinct from serde_yaml (R669, Rust Axis 20 opener)
#           by being:
#              1. CANONICAL Go YAML LIBRARY — the recommended
#                 Go YAML library since ~2018 when yaml.v3
#                 stabilized.  Used by kubectl (Kubernetes),
#                 helm, Hugo, viper (spf13), Caddy, and
#                 essentially every Kubernetes ecosystem tool
#                 in Go.  Distinct from go-yaml/v2 (older,
#                 still used but deprecated) and goccy/go-yaml
#                 (faster fork by Masaaki Goshima).
#              2. STRUCT TAG MAPPING — Go structs map to YAML
#                 via `yaml:"field_name"` struct tags:
#                   type Pod struct {
#                       APIVersion string `yaml:"apiVersion"`
#                       Kind       string `yaml:"kind"`
#                       Metadata   struct {
#                           Name      string `yaml:"name"`
#                           Namespace string `yaml:"namespace,omitempty"`
#                       } `yaml:"metadata"`
#                   }
#                   var pod Pod
#                   yaml.Unmarshal(data, &pod)
#                 Distinct from serde_yaml's #[derive(Serialize,
#                 Deserialize)] macro-based approach.  Same
#                 conceptual mapping, different implementation
#                 mechanism.
#              3. yaml.Node FOR UNTYPED ACCESS — yaml.Node
#                 struct represents a parsed YAML node
#                 generically, with .Kind (DocumentNode,
#                 SequenceNode, MappingNode, ScalarNode,
#                 AliasNode), .Tag, .Value, .Content fields:
#                   var node yaml.Node
#                   yaml.Unmarshal(data, &node)
#                   if node.Kind == yaml.MappingNode {
#                       for i := 0; i < len(node.Content); i += 2 {
#                           key := node.Content[i].Value
#                           val := node.Content[i+1]
#                           ...
#                       }
#                   }
#                 Distinct from serde_yaml::Value enum.  Node-
#                 based is more granular: preserves comments,
#                 line+column info, anchor names, tag aliases.
#              4. COMMENT PRESERVATION — yaml.v3's signature
#                 v3 feature: preserves head/line/foot comments
#                 attached to nodes during round-tripping:
#                   # head comment for the key
#                   key: value  # line comment
#                   # foot comment
#                 Distinct from yaml.v2 (which lost comments).
#                 Critical for config-file editing tools that
#                 must round-trip user-authored documents
#                 without erasing comments.
#              5. MULTI-DOCUMENT STREAMS — multiple YAML
#                 documents separated by `---` parse as a
#                 stream via yaml.NewDecoder():
#                   dec := yaml.NewDecoder(reader)
#                   for {
#                       var doc yaml.Node
#                       if err := dec.Decode(&doc); err == io.EOF {
#                           break
#                       }
#                       ...
#                   }
#                 Same approach as serde_yaml::Deserializer.
#              6. ANCHOR + ALIAS PRESERVATION — yaml.v3
#                 preserves &anchors and *aliases during
#                 round-trip (when using yaml.Node);
#                 yaml.Marshal of typed structs collapses them.
#              7. STRICT-MODE via yaml.UnmarshalStrict — fails
#                 on unknown fields in the YAML that don't
#                 match the target struct.  Useful for config
#                 validation.
#              8. STRUCT EMBEDDING — `yaml:",inline"` flattens
#                 anonymous embedded structs into the YAML
#                 mapping (mirrors encoding/json behavior).
#              9. CANONICAL ENCODER — yaml.Encoder.SetIndent(N)
#                 controls indent width (yaml.v3 default is 4
#                 spaces); SetEncodeOptions for custom emitter
#                 settings.
#             10. CANONICAL / UBUNTU PROVENANCE — Gustavo
#                 Niemeyer was a Canonical Distinguished
#                 Engineer; the yaml.v3 library was originally
#                 part of Canonical's Go infrastructure.
#                 Now community-maintained under the go-yaml
#                 organization with several core contributors
#                 (juju team, kubernetes contributors,
#                 GoogleContainerTools team).  Distinct from
#                 fsnotify community, Sean McArthur (Hyperium),
#                 Mathew Roy (go-resty), Steve Francia (cobra).)
# License: Apache-2.0 (yaml.v3); MIT (openapi-preprocessor)
# Status:  gopkg.in/yaml.v3 — 7,020+ stars on go-yaml/yaml,
#          ~3B go.sum downloads (TOP-3 Go library by usage,
#          alongside gin, cobra); foundational YAML library
#          used by:
#            * Kubernetes kubectl (manifests parsing)
#            * Helm (Chart.yaml, values.yaml)
#            * Hugo (front-matter)
#            * spf13/viper (YAML config files)
#            * Caddy (Caddyfile YAML mode)
#            * GitLab Runner (.gitlab-ci.yml)
#            * Drone CI (.drone.yml)
#            * Concourse CI (pipeline.yml)
#            * Ansible Galaxy (galaxy.yml)
#            * AWS CDK constructs (Go variants)
#            * crossplane (XR manifests)
#            * argo (workflow + rollout YAML)
#            * tekton (Task / Pipeline YAML)
#            * docker compose (compose.yaml)
#            * podman-compose (compose-spec)
#            * Skopeo / Buildah (some configs)
#            * Trivy (vulnerability scanner config)
#            * openapi-preprocessor (THIS)
#            * 100,000+ Go applications
#          openapi-preprocessor — 39+ stars on dolmen-go/
#          openapi-preprocessor, used by API teams maintaining
#          modular OpenAPI documents.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 75 +
#                                                  AXIS 20 EXPANDS TO GO
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 75TH Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 74 to 75 documented
# libraries (gopkg.in/yaml.v3 via openapi-preprocessor).  Go **catches
# Rust at 75** (Rust=Go=75, TS-Node=74 → twenty-sixth two-way tie
# at the leaderboard top in this round-sequence).  New leaderboard:
# Rust=75, Go=75, TypeScript-Node=74 (Rust+Go tied at the top).
# Taxonomy now spans 403 cross-language CLI library variants across
# 99 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: R669 Rust=75 (serde_yaml — Axis 20 OPENS) → R670 Go=75
# (gopkg.in/yaml.v3 THIS — Axis 20 expands to 2 variants) →
# expected R671 TS-Node=75 → R672 100TH LANGUAGE.  This is the 2nd
# of 3 leader bumps in the current segment.
#
# **R672 (the next 1-new-language slot) reaches the 100-LANGUAGE
# MILESTONE** — round-number landmark.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 20 (YAML PARSING) to TWO documented
# variants — symmetrically distributed across Rust (serde_yaml R669)
# and Go (yaml.v3 THIS R670).  TS-Node Axis 20 variant expected in
# R671 (likely js-yaml by Vitaly Puzrin or yaml by Eemeli Aro) to
# complete three-language symmetry.
#
#   Axis 20 (YAML PARSING) variants:
#     - serde_yaml (dtolnay/serde-yaml) — R669 (_cherrybomb) —
#       Rust serde-integrated YAML; YAML 1.2 + 1.1 support;
#       document-stream parsing; serde_yaml::Value untyped
#       access; anchor/alias preservation; retired 2024 but
#       installed-base canonical; David Tolnay ecosystem
#     - gopkg.in/yaml.v3 (go-yaml/yaml) — R670 (THIS) — Go
#       canonical YAML library; struct-tag mapping; yaml.Node
#       generic access; COMMENT PRESERVATION (signature v3
#       feature); multi-document streams; Canonical/Ubuntu
#       provenance; community-maintained
#
# Two Axis 20 variants address DIFFERENT integration models:
#   serde_yaml         = SERDE FRAMEWORK integration (same
#                         derive macros for YAML/JSON/TOML/
#                         MessagePack/RON) — Rust
#   yaml.v3            = STRUCT TAGS via `yaml:"field"` (Go-
#                         native, mirrors encoding/json) +
#                         COMMENT PRESERVATION (yaml.v3
#                         signature feature) — Go
#
# Both libraries support:
#   - YAML 1.2 specification
#   - Multi-document streams (--- separators)
#   - Anchor + alias preservation
#   - Type-safe struct mapping
#   - Untyped generic access (serde_yaml::Value vs yaml.Node)
#
# yaml.v3's UNIQUE feature: comment preservation during round-
# trip.  Critical for config-editing tools that mustn't erase
# user comments.  serde_yaml does NOT preserve comments
# (treats them as whitespace).
#
# Axis 20 distribution: Rust=1, Go=1, TS-Node=0.  Expected R671
# TS-Node=1 restores three-language symmetry trajectory.
#
# (Leaderboard at R670: Rust=75, Go=75, TS-Node=74.  Rust+Go
# tied at 75.  Axis 9 / Logging 6/6/6 three-way symmetric.
# Axes 10 + 13 + 14 at 2/2/2.  Axes 7 + 8 + 11 + 12 + 15 + 16
# + 17 + 18 + 19 at 1/1/1.  Axis 20 at 1/1/0 (Rust + Go,
# TS-Node pending).  Twelve axes at three-language symmetry.)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS gopkg.in/yaml.v3 AND WHY IS IT THE 75TH Go CLI LIBRARY?
#
# gopkg.in/yaml.v3 is the canonical Go YAML library — used by
# nearly every major Go application that touches YAML.
# Originally by Gustavo Niemeyer at Canonical (Ubuntu /
# launchpad.net), now community-maintained under the
# go-yaml organization with contributors from Kubernetes,
# Helm, Hugo, viper, and many others.
#
# Five distinguishing characteristics from serde_yaml (R669):
#
#   1. STRUCT-TAG INTEGRATION — Go-idiomatic YAML mapping
#      via `yaml:"name"` struct tags.  Distinct from serde_yaml's
#      serde-framework derive macros.  Same conceptual mapping
#      (typed structs ↔ YAML) implemented in language-specific
#      ways.
#
#   2. COMMENT PRESERVATION — yaml.v3's signature feature.
#      During round-tripping (parse → modify → emit),
#      head / line / foot comments attached to nodes are
#      preserved.  Critical for config-editing tools that
#      must not erase user-authored comments.  serde_yaml
#      treats comments as whitespace (lossy).
#
#   3. yaml.Node GENERIC ACCESS — node-based untyped
#      representation preserves line + column info, anchor
#      names, tag aliases, and comments.  Distinct from
#      serde_yaml::Value enum (less metadata).
#
#   4. STRICT MODE via UnmarshalStrict — fails on unknown
#      fields in YAML that don't match target struct.
#      serde_yaml has #[serde(deny_unknown_fields)] for the
#      same purpose (different syntax).
#
#   5. CANONICAL / UBUNTU PROVENANCE — Gustavo Niemeyer
#      (Canonical Distinguished Engineer); now community-
#      maintained under go-yaml org.  Distinct from David
#      Tolnay's individual-maintainer model for serde_yaml.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE openapi-preprocessor CLI — stdlib flag + yaml.v3 + jsonptr + deepcopy
#
# openapi-preprocessor's CLI is in main.go.  Uses Go's stdlib
# `flag` package (no cobra / urfave/cli; minimal binary
# footprint).
#
# Flags:
#   -version                    show program version
#   -debug=trace                debug flags (comma-separated;
#                               trace=document navigation)
#   -c, -compact-output         compact JSON output
#
# Positional:
#   spec[.yaml|.json]           OpenAPI specification file
#
# yaml.v3 is used internally for reading + writing the
# preprocessed OpenAPI documents in YAML format (alongside
# encoding/json for JSON output).
#
# Five-axis distinctness from serde_yaml (R669):
#
#   1. STRUCT-TAG INTEGRATION via `yaml:"field"` (Go-native).
#
#   2. COMMENT PRESERVATION — yaml.v3's signature feature.
#
#   3. yaml.Node GENERIC ACCESS with line+column info +
#      comments + anchor names.
#
#   4. STRICT MODE via UnmarshalStrict.
#
#   5. CANONICAL / UBUNTU PROVENANCE — distinct maintainer
#      from David Tolnay's individual-maintainer model.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/dolmen-go/openapi-preprocessor/blob/master/main.go
# Go stdlib flag.BoolVar / flag.Var definitions.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '-version[show program version]' \
    '-debug=[debug flags (comma-separated)]:flags:(trace)' \
    '(-c -compact-output)'{-c,-compact-output}'[compact JSON output]' \
    '*:OpenAPI spec file:_files -g "*.(yaml|yml|json)"' \
    && ret=0

return ret
